<section id="sect-00002">
<title>Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy</title>
<para id="para-00002">Hydrogens on carbon next to an ether oxygen are shifted downfield from the normal alkane resonance and show <sup>1</sup>H NMR absorptions in the region 3.4 to 4.5 <emphasis effect="italics">δ</emphasis>. This downfield shift is clearly seen in the spectrum of dipropyl ether shown in <link target-id="fig-00003"/>.</para>
<figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
<media alt="An illustration shows 1H NMR spectrum of dipropyl ether. The horizontal axis shows “chemical shift (delta)” starting from 10 ppm on the left to 0 ppm on the right at the interval of 1 unit. The vertical axis shows increasing intensity. The chemical structure of dipropyl ether shows the hydrogen atoms of the methyl group in blue; hydrogen atoms of methylene groups bonded to methyl groups in green; hydrogen atoms of methylene groups bonded to oxygen atom in pink. The left corner of the graph shows chemical shifts as 0.92 1.58 and 3.36 at relative area 1.50 1.00 and 1.00. Four pink peaks of variable heights are shown between 4 and 3 delta; Six green peaks of gradually increasing height and decreasing are shown between 3 and 2 delta. Two small medium and tall peaks of equal height are shown. Few green peaks of variable heights are shown between 3 and 2 delta. Few blue peaks of variable heights are shown immediately after 1 delta with the tallest of all peaks shown here. A short peak labeled as pink “TMS” is shown at 0 delta.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_09_003.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption><emphasis effect="bold">The <sup>1</sup>H NMR spectrum of dipropyl ether</emphasis>. Protons on carbon next to oxygen are shifted downfield to 3.4 <emphasis effect="italics">δ.</emphasis></caption>
</figure>
<para id="para-00003">Epoxides absorb at a slightly higher field than other ethers and show characteristic resonances at 2.5 to 3.5 <emphasis effect="italics">δ</emphasis> in their <sup>1</sup>H NMR spectra, as indicated for 1,2-epoxypropane in <link target-id="fig-00004"/>. The methylene protons of this epoxide are diastereotopic, and display complex splitting (see <link document="m00150"/> and <link document="m00151"/>).</para>
<figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
<media alt="An illustration shows 1H NMR spectrum of 1 2-epoxypropane. The horizontal axis shows “chemical shift (delta)” starting from 10 ppm on the left to 0 ppm on the right at the interval of 1 unit. The vertical axis shows increasing intensity. The chemical structure of 1 2-epoxypropane shows a methyl group bonded to methine group bonded to methylene group. The carbon atom of the methine group and of the methylene group are bonded to a common oxygen atom forming three-membered structure. The hydrogen atom of the methyl group is in blue; methine group in green; methylene group in pink. The left corner of the graph shows chemical shifts as1.32 2.42 2.75 and 2.97 at relative area 3.00 1.00 1.00 and 1.00. Few small green peaks of almost the same height are shown at 3 delta. 2 sets of pink peaks of almost the same height are shown between 3 and 2 delta. Few tall blue peaks are shown between 2 and 1 delta. Two separate blue peaks are shown soon after 1 delta. A short peak labeled as pink “TMS” is shown at 0 delta.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_18_09_004.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption><emphasis effect="bold">The <sup>1</sup>H NMR spectrum of 1,2-epoxypropane</emphasis>.</caption>
</figure>
<para id="para-00004">Ether carbon atoms also exhibit a downfield shift in the <sup>13</sup>C NMR spectrum, where they usually absorb in the 50 to 80 <emphasis effect="italics">δ</emphasis> range. For example, the carbon atoms next to oxygen in methyl propyl ether absorb at 58.5 and 74.8 <emphasis effect="italics">δ</emphasis>. Similarly, the methyl carbon in anisole absorbs at 54.8 <emphasis effect="italics">δ</emphasis>.</para>
